result.execSummary:
The defendant Kaylynn Marie Samplaski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).
  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Kaylynn Marie Samplaski in court with attorney Gary S. Cirilli and Jeff Joy.  Defendant Kaylynn Marie Samplaski in custody.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 8:58 AM. State - here for a review filed by defense counsel. Joy and Cirilli makes argument in regards to the release date of the defendant, Sheriff has allowed good time for first year of the sentence. Court clarifies that counts #1 and #4 are concurrent to each other, not consecutive as the JOC states, amend JOC on this matter to state Concurrent and not Consecutive. Discussion begins regarding the 3rd year of jail that was originally stayed and she needed to get a job for that to be stayed. Court responds, instructs parties to bring proof of her schooling and jobs applied for. Court wants clarification from the jail in regards to huber/school with the defendant. Recess to get jail administrator here. Recalled at 9:25 AM. Court asks questions of the Jail Administrator. Administrator responds and states what records he has. Court again asks for whatever records can be given to the court in regards to her GED classes that she has taken and what applications she has turned in. Cirilli asks if her participation in Koinonia would satisfy the AODA requirement. Discussion on that. Court states that the Koinonia time will satisfy the AODA requirement. If the defendant becomes full time employed or school, that will satisfy the Court. Joy states that the defendant can take a test within the next two weeks. Court wants the program schedule for school/GED. Court will allow the defendant to be released to go and take a test. Joy - needs to get out for the intensive prep that is needed to take the test. Court is convinced that there has been issues in getting these things accomplished. Court instructs that the defendant should be released for taking a test and job interviews but the interviews/tests need to be verified by the Sheriff/FOSO. Court makes statement to the defendant on his intent when sentencing was handed down.
From Attorney Joy requesting defendant be allowed to attend weekly meetings and Spring Fling - transportation to be provided by Koinonia. Approved by Judge Stenz.

From Attorney Joy - requesting transfer of inpatient treatment facilities. Approved by Judge Stenz upon same terms and conditions of propro approval of 3/10/16, which were: Sentence stayed and she may be released to undergo inpatient treatment. She must return directly to jail, upon completion or termination of the treatment, to complete the balance of the sentence.

Defendant Kaylynn Marie Samplaski in court with attorney Gary S. Cirilli.  Defendant Kaylynn Marie Samplaski in custody.  No other appearances. Called at 4:15 PM. Court warns witness regarding his attitude 4:43 pm. Kennedy asks for continuance. Court questions witness 4:45 pm. Cirilli recross 4:47 pm. Kennedy questions 4:49 pm. Witness excused 4:50 pm. Kennedy makes statement no objection to continuance and believes that money should be refunded to Mr Thunder. 4:51 pm Cirilli makes statement believes that Samplaski's testimony more credible and has not proven that the money is Mr Thunder's. Court finds Samplaski more credible for stated reasons. Court finds that it was either Ms Samplaski's money or her mother's money. Court not aware if Mr Thunder can seek other remedies to get the money back. Court denies motion. Adj 4:57 pm.
